{
  "doc_id": "43197",
  "text": "Lifestyle factors, which increase the risk of obesity, tend to cluster in families [CITATION_1] . The Avon Longitudinal Study of Parents and Children has reported that certain diet patterns tend to be similar in couples [CITATION_2] . Studies have reported on the associations with children's patterns and the influence of their parents [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Fisk et al. have reported on maternal influences on dietary patterns in three year old children and found that children scoring highly on a prudent diet pattern were more likely to have mothers with similar prudent diet patterns [CITATION_6] . Studies of diet and child obesity have tended to focus on maternal influences with limited evidence available for the father's diet. However, a recent animal model has highlighted the potential for paternal programming of obesity [CITATION_7] .",
